OpenAI Launches GPT Store
-------------------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-01-10/openai-=
launches-gpt-store-for-users-to-share-custom-chatbots ) :

OpenAI has launched an online store where people can share customized versi=
ons of the company=E2=80=99s popular ChatGPT chatbot, after initially delay=
ing the rollout because of leadership upheaval last year. The new store, wh=
ich rolled out Wednesday to paid ChatGPT users, will corral the chatbots th=
at users create for a variety of tasks, for example a version of ChatGPT th=
at can teach math to a child or come up with colorful cocktail recipes.

The product, called the GPT Store, will include chatbots that users have ch=
osen to share publicly. It will eventually introduce ways for people to mak=
e money from their creations =E2=80=94 much as they might through the app s=
tores of Apple Inc. or Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s Google. Similar to those app=
 stores, OpenAI=E2=80=99s GPT Store will let users see the most popular and=
 trending chatbots on a leaderboard and search for them by category. In a b=
log post announcing the rollout, OpenAI said that people have made 3 millio=
n custom chatbots thus far, though it was not clear how many were available=
 through its store at launch.

That last sentence is important; from said blog post ( https://openai.com/b=
log/introducing-the-gpt-store ) :

It=E2=80=99s been two months since we announced GPTs, and users have alread=
y created over 3 million custom versions of ChatGPT. Many builders have sha=
red their GPTs for others to use. Today, we=E2=80=99re starting to roll out=
 the GPT Store to ChatGPT Plus, Team and Enterprise users so you can find u=
seful and popular GPTs. Visit chat.openai.com/gpts to explore.

The store features a diverse range of GPTs developed by our partners and th=
e community. Browse popular and trending GPTs on the community leaderboard,=
 with categories like DALL=C2=B7E, writing, research, programming, educatio=
n, and lifestyle. We will also highlight useful and impactful GPTs [every w=
eek]=E2=80=A6

The GPT Store is dissimilar from, say, the iPhone App Store in that it is n=
ot the exclusive place to get GPTs (yes, OpenAI has successfully claimed th=
e term, I think). Of course the iPhone App Store doesn=E2=80=99t have to be=
 the exclusive place to get Apps: Apple forces that to be the case, which i=
s something various regulators are seeking to loosen (John Gruber has a goo=
d Article I agree with in terms of the E.U.=E2=80=99s Digital Markets Act o=
n Daring Fireball ( https://daringfireball.net/2024/01/vestager_cook ) ). A=
 better comparison, though, might be the Mac App Store: developers can both=
 sell apps directly and have them appear in a centralized marketplace that =
consumers are more likely to check, albeit with more restrictions on the ap=
ps technically (i.e. they must operate in a sandbox, for example, which mea=
ns much more limited access to the computer or other apps).

The key takeaway is this: the GPT Store is very much an Aggregation play, a=
long the lines of the proposed Plugin store ( https://stratechery.com/2023/=
the-accidental-consumer-tech-company-chatgpt-meta-and-product-market-fit-ag=
gregation-and-apis/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNo=
ZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYX=
NzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVya=
SI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL3RoZS1hY2NpZGVudGFsLWNvbnN1bWVy=
LXRlY2gtY29tcGFueS1jaGF0Z3B0LW1ldGEtYW5kLXByb2R1Y3QtbWFya2V0LWZpdC1hZ2dyZWd=
hdGlvbi1hbmQtYXBpcy8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTcwNzk5NTI2MiwiaWF0IjoxNzA1NDAzMjYyLCJpc3=
MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZ=
CBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1=
YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.VnT0EUq-r2UPlp-S=
NItDS23JFjh-Zv9X2W8MhrLGhYz18EM4ypyAglU0AH2JXPwfEzNwPz4JnxSHLdDvUHK_jRgcwap=
Xb5YJvwl6gRoB78VnT2WVm3Ee29-OwxIjRoH2-Aq6aiulW6Ef_SGgz0-GSThGOuLYH2vCR_GYQf=
OK_aUvABzi3NRUPpCh3f2lAo1zdROyLrJRF48K_L-tCl1eaT67oRl3Zl9fbkJrZ-Z4O79Zyxa7O=
jPD5-yCjMojYwzTemJ3Ws3imyyv98WtW3WXawz9QT4Y6BFgo2Be25Bh8UEuTbqX7MT9JxYTYnaJ=
jN2kfzM_GmzMg9y816AzFn727A ) , which was the v1 attempt at building a 3rd-p=
arty platform on top of ChatGPT. Tens of millions of users are already accu=
stomed to going to ChatGPT, and now OpenAI can leverage that control of dem=
and to create a marketplace for augmented versions of GPT built by develope=
rs.

This, to be clear, isn=E2=80=99t a criticism or limitation, either: a disco=
very mechanism is critical. Just look at that 3 million number: that may se=
em unnaturally large, but that is because creating a custom GPT is very eas=
y. This is a point that OpenAI COO Brad Lightcap made in an interview with =
Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/newsletters/2024-01-11/openai-s-=
coo-pitches-startup-as-friendly-partner-to-publishers ) when asked if the G=
PT Store would be like the App Store:

I think it could be bigger. It=E2=80=99s a lot of work to build a single iO=
S app. If you look at what GPTs are, that can be spun up quickly, configure=
d quickly. We=E2=80=99ll make it easier and easier for them to have accessi=
bility into other services in other parts of your workflow. Some of them wi=
ll be fun; some of them will be for work. So you get a lot of diversity the=
re. I expect there can be many thousands of GPTs that any individual person=
 ever comes in contact with specific to the things they want to do.

The App Store is definitely an Aggregator, but Lightcap is right that the p=
rice of entry for suppliers (i.e. developers) is non-trivial. Compare that =
to Google on the other end of the spectrum: Google=E2=80=99s supply is the =
entire web, and the price of entry is whatever effort it takes to create a =
webpage or type a reply on Reddit or a forum. GPTs aren=E2=80=99t quite tha=
t easy, but they are absolutely a lot easier than making an app, which mean=
s it is definitely plausible or even likely that there will be more GPTs th=
an apps (but not as many as the number of web pages). That, by extension, m=
akes an Aggregator all the more useful and, ultimately, valuable.

The Everything Engine and Advertising
-------------------------------------

I mentioned above that the Mac App Store imposes some extra limitations on =
apps relative to what you can sell on the open web; the GPT store has some =
rules of its own, as highlighted by Allen Pike in a post entitled From Chat=
bot to Everything Engine ( https://allenpike.com/2024/chatbot-to-everything=
-engine ) :

While GPTs may prove useful in their current form, they=E2=80=99re part of =
a grander plan. The exact path is yet to be seen, but I believe OpenAI tipp=
ed their hand with a very specific choice in how GPTs are designed.

Pike observed that most chatbots open with a question to get the conversati=
on started, but that that approach is explicitly not allowed for GPTs in th=
e GPT Store: they must silently wait for the user to initiate the conversat=
ion. Pike found this frustrating as a developer, but made the case this may=
 very well be in service to a grander vision:

While GPTs may seem like they have similar problems, they offer a clear evo=
lutionary path to a low friction, scaleable, and potentially highly profita=
ble user experience. In a world where many useful GPTs exist, and those GPT=
s are written to respond to user input rather than start conversations with=
 people who select them, ChatGPT can incrementally become an Everything Eng=
ine simply by routing requests to the best GPT for the job.

Let=E2=80=99s say you ask ChatGPT, =E2=80=9CCan you help me with this math =
problem?=E2=80=9D it could offer to send your query to the Khan Academy GPT=
, built by learning experts. If you ask, =E2=80=9CHow are the markets today=
?=E2=80=9D it could sub into Yahoo Finance=E2=80=99s stock market GPT, equi=
pped with realtime market APIs. If you ask an Everything Engine =E2=80=9CWh=
ere should I go on vacation?=E2=80=9D it might leverage a travel expert=E2=
=80=99s lovingly crafted GPT for helping you consider your options.

Just joking, it=E2=80=99ll offer the Tripadvisor GPT. Or whoever the highes=
t bidder was. We won=E2=80=99t see sponsored GPT results for a while, but a=
n Everything Engine would be the most compelling ad opportunity since web s=
earch results pages. If it works, the incentive for OpenAI to accept paymen=
t for GPT promotion will be immense.

Pike is unsure if OpenAI will truly go in this direction, but argues that G=
oogle likely will, and I think he makes a good case. This would be, at leas=
t in the beginning, a win-win: chatbots leverage developers to dramatically=
 increase their capabilities, making them even more compelling to users, an=
d developers will pay for the right to be the default answer provider. Pike=
 adds:

If I=E2=80=99m right =E2=80=93 if a model and ecosystem like GPTs can be us=
ed to build a compelling Everything Engine =E2=80=93 then an ad-supported E=
verything Engine is coming. I=E2=80=99m more than willing to pay $20/mo for=
 ChatGPT Plus, but most people won=E2=80=99t. But they will visit a free we=
bsite where they can type into a text field, and it will answer their quest=
ions with ads.

I have heard arguments that people will have much less tolerance for =E2=80=
=9Cfree=E2=80=9D in an AI world. Imagine a not-too-distant future of dramat=
ically more capable AIs with persistent memory and context that become deep=
ly enmeshed in your life: do you really want to be using something like tha=
t for free, given that you are paying with far more personally relevant dat=
a than anything before it, simply because you are involving the AI in every=
 aspect of your life? And yet people do engage with Google in particular in=
 that way: their email and calendar are with Gmail, every search is with Go=
ogle, and all of their web browsing is in Chrome. There are paid (or in the=
 case of Apple products more privacy-centric) alternatives, but the reveale=
d preference of the vast majority of people is that free matters most, as l=
ong as the product is good.

Moreover, there is the reality that advertising of some sort is always the =
end game of an Aggregator. Aggregating demand is, at its core, about aggreg=
ating attention, and while the initial goal may be to direct that attention=
 to a web page or an app or whatever supply it is that needs discovery from=
 the Aggregator, the best way to monetize that aggregated attention is to c=
harge entities that are willing to explicitly pay for attention. We call th=
em advertisers.

Artifact Shuts Down
-------------------

From Kevin Systrom on Medium ( https://medium.com/artifact-news/shutting-do=
wn-artifact-1e70de46d419 ) :

We=E2=80=99ve made the decision to wind down operations of the Artifact app=
. We launched a year ago and since then we=E2=80=99ve been working tireless=
ly to build a great product. We have built something that a core group of u=
sers love, but we have concluded that the market opportunity isn=E2=80=99t =
big enough to warrant continued investment in this way. It=E2=80=99s easy f=
or startups to ignore this reality, but often making the tough call earlier=
 is better for everyone involved. The biggest opportunity cost is time work=
ing on newer, bigger and better things that have the ability to reach many =
millions of people. I am personally excited to continue building new things=
, though only time will tell what that might be. We live in an exciting tim=
e where artificial intelligence is changing just about everything we touch,=
 and the opportunities for new ideas seem limitless.

We had a good discussion of this news on today=E2=80=99s episode of Ditheri=
ng ( https://dithering.fm ) , but looking at my own (steadily declining to =
nothing) Artifact usage, what stands out to me is that the content Artifact=
 was attempting to surface was just too crappy. I get the fact that Artifac=
t was designed to get better the more you used it =E2=80=94 itself a bit of=
 a fatal flaw given you need to hook people right away =E2=80=94 but I felt=
 like the more I used the product the more frustrated I got with clickbait =
articles from sites rewriting other sites (on webpages chock full of ads).

In theory, the promise of an AI-driven content recommender is that it doesn=
=E2=80=99t matter how much dreck is out there: the goal is to only surface =
the good stuff. That raises a further question: was Artifact=E2=80=99s AI j=
ust not good enough, or is there simply not that much good content on the w=
eb these days? The answer is probably a bit of both, but there is a reason =
I made the case last week ( https://stratechery.com/2024/the-new-york-times=
-ai-opportunity/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ=
